  {
    "client_msg_id": "89c1c798-12e6-432a-ab38-adc268471810",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "<@UN9SCH5RD> New knowledge most often arises in the context of deep thinking, so... :slightly_smiling_face:\n\n<@UAJKEBGP8> I find the characterization of the difference in development process between older and newer languages in this post a bit odd. For example, the first Lisp interpreter was a weekend hack by Slug Russell and C was bashed together quite quickly by non-academic practitioners to solve their own problems. Most of the grand pseudo-academic committee languages of yesteryear were popular failures, like PL/I and ADA, and the ones that succeeded did so largely because of massive corporate propaganda efforts (Cobol, Java).",
    "user": "U013ZLJARC7",
    "ts": "1608287655.398100",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "source_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
