              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " New knowledge most often arises in the context of deep thinking, so... "
              },
              {
                "type": "emoji",
                "name": "slightly_smiling_face"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "\n\n"
              },
              {
                "type": "user",
                "user_id": "UAJKEBGP8"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " I find the characterization of the difference in development process between older and newer languages in this post a bit odd. For example, the first Lisp interpreter was a weekend hack by Slug Russell and C was bashed together quite quickly by non-academic practitioners to solve their own problems. Most of the grand pseudo-academic committee languages of yesteryear were popular failures, like PL/I and ADA, and the ones that succeeded did so largely because of massive corporate propaganda efforts (Cobol, Java)."
              }
            ]
